The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Business Briefs
                              
	 New Delhi, July 20: Trading giant MMTC today received mandatory approval for splitting its share with a face value of Rs 10 into 10 scrips of Re 1 each and issuing one-to-one bonus shares. The extraordinary general meeting (EGM) of the Rs 45,260-crore MMTC was convened here. With the stock split and bonus issue, the companys floating stock goes up, though a majority remains with the government, a top official said.                            
	 Calcutta, July 20: Bankrupt South Korean auto company SsangYong Motor has extended the last date for submission of financial bids to August 10 from July 20 on bidders request. In response to our request, SsangYong Motors has extended the time for financial bid to August 10, a spokesman for the Ruia group said.                             
	 New York, July 20: Goldman Sachs today posted an 83 per cent plunge in second-quarter profit at $453 million after being hit by expenses related to settlement of fraud charges with market regulatory SEC, as well as UK bonus tax. The bank had posted a profit of $2.7 billion in the year-ago period.                            
	 Mumbai, July 20: Alstom Holdings and Schneider Electric Group today postponed their open offer to buy a 20 per cent stake in Areva T amp;D India till further notice.                             
	 Mumbai, July 20: Hyderabad-based SKS Microfinance plans to hit the capital markets with an initial public offering on July 28 to raise around Rs 1,500 crore.                             
	 Chennai, July 20: The Indian Overseas Bank (IOB) will focus on rural penetration and building its overseas presence for growth, chairman Suhas Anand Bhat said.                             
	 New Delhi, July 20: Mangalore Refinery and Petrochemicals (MRPL) today said its expansion programme had got stuck because of a land dispute with a local farmer in Mangalore resulting in a loss of Rs 600 crore.
                                                                                                                          
